# Layer 1 — Observation Layer: Deep-Dive Build Specification

*Hand this to the coding agent (Copilot / Claude 4.6). It is a complete specification for ONE layer. Build only this. No other layer, no LLM, no real application data required to build or test it.*

---

## 1. Purpose & scope

Build a standalone Python module that, given a live browser page, returns **one complete, structured list of every interactive element currently on screen** — including the elements that standard DOM agents silently miss. This module is the foundation of an enterprise web-exploration agent. If this layer is incomplete, every layer above it fails. Therefore it is built and validated in isolation, first.

**In scope:** observe the current screen and emit a structured element list.
**Out of scope (do NOT build):** the exploration loop, navigation, memory/graph, authentication, framework detection, any LLM call, any code generation. Those are separate later specs.

---

## 2. Why this layer exists (rationale the agent needs to make good choices)

Standard browser agents build an indexed list of clickable elements from the DOM and act on it. On complex enterprise apps (Material UI / React / Salesforce Lightning) that list is **incomplete**, so the agent acts on the wrong element, nothing changes, and it retries forever. The list breaks for five specific reasons. This module exists to defeat all five:

1. **React Portals** — MUI renders Dialogs, Menus, Select dropdowns, Tooltips and Popovers into a node appended to the end of `<body>`, detached from the trigger. A naive walk associates them wrongly or misses them.
2. **Shadow DOM** — Salesforce Lightning and many design-system components live inside shadow roots. XPath-based paths cannot cross shadow boundaries.
3. **Virtualization** — MUI DataGrid / react-window render only visible rows. A naive walk sees 12 rows in a 10,000-row grid.
4. **Iframes** — embedded/legacy content (e.g. Salesforce VisualForce) lives in a separate frame context that a top-level walk ignores.
5. **Visually identical components** — every MUI IconButton is a grey circle; pixels can't disambiguate them. Role + accessible name can.

---

## 3. Functional requirements — what it MUST capture, and the technique for each

### 3.1 Light DOM interactive elements
Capture: buttons, links, inputs, textareas, selects, checkboxes, radios, switches, sliders, tabs, accordions/expanders, and any element with an interactive role (`role="button"`, `role="menuitem"`, `role="tab"`, etc.) or a click handler signal.

### 3.2 Open Shadow DOM — recursively
Inject JavaScript via `page.evaluate()` that walks the document **and descends into every `element.shadowRoot`**, at every nesting level (shadow roots inside shadow roots). Reference technique (illustrative, not the final implementation):

```js
function deepCollect(root, acc) {
  root.querySelectorAll('*').forEach(el => {
    if (isInteractive(el)) acc.push(describe(el));
    if (el.shadowRoot) deepCollect(el.shadowRoot, acc); // descend
  });
  return acc;
}
```

- Handle **closed** shadow roots gracefully: they cannot be pierced. Detect their presence (the host exists but `shadowRoot` is null on a custom element) and record a `closed_shadow_host` marker so we know coverage is incomplete there, rather than silently dropping it.
- Note: Playwright's CSS locator engine pierces *open* shadow roots automatically, so generated CSS locators for these elements remain usable downstream.

### 3.3 Same-origin iframes
Enumerate `page.frames()`, run the same deep walk inside each **same-origin** frame, and tag every element with its `frame_path`. For **cross-origin** frames (cannot be read), record a `cross_origin_frame` marker with no contents — again, so coverage gaps are explicit, not hidden.

### 3.4 React Portals / overlays
After the main walk, scan body-level overlay containers:
`[role="presentation"]`, `[role="dialog"]`, `[role="menu"]`, `[role="listbox"]`, `[role="tooltip"]`, `.MuiPopover-root`, `.MuiModal-root`, `.MuiDrawer-root`.
Tag every element found inside them with `is_overlay: true`. This is how an open menu/dialog gets correctly captured even though it lives detached at the end of `<body>`.

### 3.5 Virtualized lists
Detect a scroll container (overflow scroll/auto with `scrollHeight` much larger than `clientHeight`, or known markers like `.MuiDataGrid-virtualScroller`, `react-window` containers). Then **scroll-probe**: scroll in increments, collect newly-rendered items after each step, de-duplicate, until no new items appear or a safety cap (e.g. 500 items / 50 scrolls) is hit. Record `is_virtualized: true` and an approximate total. Never report only the initially-visible rows as the full set.

### 3.6 Accessibility tree merge
Call `page.accessibility.snapshot()` and merge `role` + accessible `name` onto the collected elements (match by bounding box / node identity). This disambiguates visually identical components and gives every element a human-meaningful label even when visible text is empty.

