## 9. Real-app validation + sanitized failure report (the loop back)

After public tests pass, the user runs `observe()` against the real enterprise app **privately, in their own environment.** No application data leaves the network.

When something is wrong, the coding agent should produce a **sanitized failure report** in the format below. This contains only structural/technical facts — enough for the architect to diagnose and revise the spec — and **never** any business data.

**Allowed in the report:** failure category, generic technical symptom, structural counts.
**Forbidden in the report:** real URLs/domains, screenshots, field labels, button text, any entered or displayed data values, app or customer names.

```json
{
  "failure_category": "PORTAL_MISSED | SHADOW_NOT_PIERCED | CLOSED_SHADOW_ROOT |
                       IFRAME_CROSS_ORIGIN | VIRTUALIZATION_NOT_DETECTED |
                       ELEMENT_NOT_FOUND | TIMEOUT | OTHER",
  "symptom": "generic description, e.g. 'a menu was visually open but observe() returned 0 overlay elements'",
  "structural_facts": {
    "total_elements_captured": 0,
    "frames_present": 0,
    "same_origin_frames_captured": 0,
    "closed_shadow_hosts": 0,
    "elements_with_empty_accessible_name": 0
  },
  "coverage_warnings": ["..."]
}
```

Example of a good report: *"Category PORTAL_MISSED. Symptom: after the bottom-right action button was clicked and a menu was visually open, observe() returned 0 elements tagged is_overlay. structural_facts: total_elements_captured 41, frames_present 0, closed_shadow_hosts 0."* — That tells the architect exactly what to fix, with zero company data.

